---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---
<DocsLayout
  title="shuttle provision"
  description="Bootstrap a fresh Debian/Ubuntu VPS with Docker, Caddy, a deploy user, SSH hardening, and firewall configuration."
  section="commands"
>
  <p>
    <code>shuttle provision</code> automates the one-time server setup required to receive
    Shuttle deploys. It connects as root and runs a 9-step bootstrap sequence that transforms a
    bare Debian or Ubuntu VPS into a production-ready deployment target.
  </p>
  <p>
    You only need to run this once per server. After provisioning, use <code>shuttle deploy</code>
    for all subsequent releases.
  </p>

  <h2>Usage</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle provision
</code></pre>
  <p>
    Shuttle will prompt for confirmation before making any changes. It reads your SSH public key
    from <code>~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub</code> or <code>~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub</code> automatically.
  </p>

  <h2>9-step provisioning process</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Connect as root</strong> — opens an SSH connection to the server using your local
      SSH key. Root access is required for this step only; subsequent deploys use the deploy user.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Detect OS</strong> — reads <code>/etc/os-release</code> and verifies the server is
      running Debian or Ubuntu. Other distributions are not currently supported.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Create deploy user</strong> — creates the SSH user specified in your
      <code>shuttle.yml</code> (e.g., <code>deploy</code>). Adds your SSH public key to
      <code>~/.ssh/authorized_keys</code> and grants the user passwordless <code>sudo</code> access
      for Docker commands.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Install Docker</strong> — installs Docker Engine using Docker's official apt
      repository. Adds the deploy user to the <code>docker</code> group so Docker commands work
      without <code>sudo</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Install Caddy container</strong> — starts the <code>caddy:2-alpine</code> Docker
      container named <code>shuttle-caddy</code> with ports 80 and 443 bound and a volume for
      Let's Encrypt certificate storage. Configured with <code>restart: always</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Configure firewall (UFW)</strong> — enables UFW and installs fail2ban. Opens ports
      22 (SSH), 80 (HTTP), and 443 (HTTPS). Firewall failures are treated as warnings since the
      server may already have an existing firewall configuration.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Harden SSH</strong> — disables password authentication
      (<code>PasswordAuthentication no</code>) and optionally disables root login
      (<code>PermitRootLogin no</code>) after the deploy user is confirmed to work.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Create project directories</strong> — creates <code>/opt/shuttle/&lt;app&gt;/</code>
      and the app working directory <code>/opt/shuttle/&lt;app&gt;/&lt;app&gt;/</code> with the
      correct ownership for the deploy user.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Verify everything works</strong> — connects as the deploy user (not root) and runs
      <code>docker ps</code> to confirm Docker access works correctly before returning success.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>A fresh Debian 11/12 or Ubuntu 22.04/24.04 server</li>
    <li>Root SSH access from your local machine</li>
    <li>An SSH public key at <code>~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub</code> or <code>~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub</code></li>
    <li>Ports 80, 443, and 22 open in your hosting provider's network-level firewall</li>
    <li>The server's hostname/IP in your <code>shuttle.yml</code> <code>server.host</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What gets installed</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Component</th>
        <th>Version</th>
        <th>Notes</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Docker Engine</td>
        <td>Latest stable</td>
        <td>From Docker's official apt repository</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Caddy</td>
        <td><code>caddy:2-alpine</code></td>
        <td>Runs as a Docker container, not a system package</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>UFW</td>
        <td>System package</td>
        <td>Firewall rules for SSH, HTTP, HTTPS</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>fail2ban</td>
        <td>System package</td>
        <td>Brute-force SSH protection</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Multi-server provisioning</h2>
  <p>
    When your <code>shuttle.yml</code> defines multiple server groups, Shuttle provisions each
    host sequentially (not in parallel, to give you visibility into each step):
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">Provisioning deploy@203.0.113.10 (group: web)...
[1/9] Connecting to 203.0.113.10 as root
...
Provisioning deploy@203.0.113.11 (group: web)...
</code></pre>

  <h2>Re-provisioning</h2>
  <p>
    Provisioning is designed to be safe to re-run. Most steps are idempotent — creating a user
    that already exists is a no-op, installing Docker when it's already installed skips the apt
    setup. Use re-provisioning to apply updated firewall rules or SSH hardening to existing servers.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
